{
  "doc_id": "55878",
  "text": "Although the presence of an efficient cellulase enzyme system is important for the digestion of cellulose, other factors might affect the efficiency of hydrolysis. Mechanical fragmentation using the mandibles and gastric mill is an important component of overall cellulose degradation [CITATION_1] . The gastric mill of G. natalis consists of sharp, robust features that are well suited to shredding plant material, thus allowing access to cellulose in the cell walls [CITATION_2] . This process increases the surface area of cellulose exposed to the enzymes within the digestive juice, therefore increasing the efficiency of enzymatic breakdown [CITATION_3] . The mechanical disruption of cellulose increases the efficiency of enzymatic breakdown by increasing the surface area of cellulose exposed to the enzymes within the digestive juice [CITATION_4] and might further reduce the need for a cellobiohydrolase by improving access to glucose residues normally buried within crystalline regions of cellulose fibres. This is in contrast to fungal and bacterial systems, which lack a mechanical mill, relying instead on the presence of a cellobiohydrolase and its synergistic activity with the endo--1,4glucanase to digest crystalline cellulose efficiently [CITATION_5] .",
